Like many others, I just feel like there was a wealth of inspiration to choose from with this theme and so few attendees thought about it and did anything interesting. There's American quilt patterns, praire/cowboy dress, clothes inspired by the miners and railroad workers that led to such an economic boom in the USA, fashion that evolved from military and camouflage clothing, outfits inspired by famous American icons and TV shows, and hell, nobody did anything referencing baseball?! Not to mention seeing clothes inspired by or made by Native Americans (with the exception of Quannah obviously), the impact of Mexican or Irish or Japanese immigrants on American fashion, and seeing black Americans role in fashion evolution would have been so great! So many possibilities and almost nobody went for them...

fyi: This is a little long. I think that some of iconography/cultural references are being missed. Iman's look imo references the African American experience in America. So I am a white person and I am not saying that I understand the African American in total and I hope that I don't offend people. But I think that Iman's look references Africa with the use of animal motifs. and decoration. A number of important goddesses and gods of the ancient world are portrayed with snakes as a symbol of power. Because the snake sheds it's skin it a symbol of rebirth and renewal. The headdress combined with the hoop skirt I think references Scarlett O'Hara as a symbol of the American South and colonization the oppressors of African Americans and people of color around the world. The visible hoops in the skirt remind me of a cage. The transformation of the southern belle hat into a lion's mane a symbol of great power combined with the snake skin bodice represent the emergence of a powerful people from oppression.  Jennifer Lopez's look is another example of layered iconography related to the colonization of the American west combined with intense channeling of Cher. This is probably a bit of a reach but those are my thoughts. Regardless Iman is a stunningly beautiful and powerful woman and this look is amazing. Jennifer Lopez is beautiful too. I love your channel and I have learned so much. Thank you.

Â @charisma-hornum-friesÂ  â€¦I mean, camels. Bison. Dogs. There are plenty. My point wasn't that "horses are only American because their ancestors originated here," my point was, "funnily enough, horses did technically come from North America." Modern horses evolved from Eurasia and Africa. However, horses are still a very American experience given how much they were used during the expansion from East to West. Native Americans, too, have a huge tie with horses after they came with the settlers.  So we have that, since the beginning of America, horses were heavily involved with our expansion. Then we have the Western-cowhand culture that can be seen down to the design of the saddle. Then we have that mustangs are commonly symbols of freedom, and used as a very American thing. Blah blah blah, I can go on.  But, this comes from someone who is very familiar with horses. That, and I gotta tell you, for something to be symbolic of a thing, like a country, it doesn't have to be only a part of that country. Horses are everywhere, but you cannot sit there and tell me that America didn't create its own version of a horse to represent itself. American Quarter Horse? Very American. Thoroughbreds, not so much (pretty English breed), but Man O' War and Secretariat? Very American horses. Just like food, architecture, etc. the experiences that go with horses can be distinctive of one culture even though literally all cultures also have food, architecture, etc.  Edit: Here's a better way to put it sinceâ€¦I just word vomited all over. Lol. (Again, very familiar with horses. Is my study/career path.) For something to be a symbol of a country, it's not about where it originates from but rather what role it plays within its culture. Horses play a huge role in American culture as its foundation; again, the Westward expansion wouldn't have happened without horses, not how it played out at least. Same kind of thing as English tea. Very British, but tea didn't originate from Western cultures, if I'm not mistaken. Lol

Just saw the Dior exhibit at the Brooklyn Museum of Art after seeing Kaia Gerber's dress on this retrospective, it is interesting to see how Oscar De La Renta referenced this Dior style.  Granted, not designed by Dior himself, Dior had stated he found and attributed much of his artistic voice in the fashion couture world through observance of American women's fashion and was a active choice in pursuit of distancing then-modern aesthetics from WWII era Parisian fashion (which he stated was in complete disarray). The "New Look", which I still think is very evident in this current dress and the referenced dress (1977)'s silhouette, was a rebellious push away from the war broken "old world" into the American "new world," shaped around the modern woman's needs/ lifestyle.  As an ideology, with the dress and its referenced structure being interpreted as a clear homage to Dior's original work, the Met Gala look is successful as a deeper metaphor towards American independence and how "the American mindset" influenced the European fashion market from the 1940s and thereby has influenced today's.

It felt like most just didn't care to do enough research for anything inspired by American History or events. We have so many instances of history and legendary events they could've pulled from. Louisiana's creole culture and french/Haitian/Indian influenced society. The fashion of down home country girls, since Cottage-core is still a thing. Fashions from the pilgrims, the roaring 20s, the dust bowl era, or even rocka-billy and the 1950's. We had the 60s flower children. The glam rock era. Disco. The poodle skirts, or the iconic go-go looks. No western themes? No Native American inspired motifs? No interesting hairstyles and jewelry to reference throwback eras? No blax-ploitation ideas? No miami vice or miami nights w/ the popularity of it's tunes and dances once upon a time? No revolutionary fashion taken w/ a modern twist? Or southern belles? Or even something creative w/ denim? No sporty looks from iconic figures or a call back to American preps? No 80s looks? No jazz or Harlem Renaissance? No Dean Martin or Rat Pack influences? No Blues Singers inspired looks?  The Met Gala was an absolute failure. The disappointment. But these people are living in bubbles. So when referencing America what did we expect? Half of them wore styles from European designers.

Here are some possible references to America that I noticed and Luke may have missed: Billie Eilish: she looks very old Hollywood, and apparently the dress was inspired by those worn by the Barbie dolls she had growing up. And Barbie is a very American creation. Cara Delevigne: the bib-vest thing resembles a few things to me, including the padding worn by a baseball catcher, and the plastic riot shields carried by police officers. Chloe Bailey: her dress gives a Statue of Liberty vibe, especially with her hair styled the way it is almost forming a crown. Debbie Harry: the silhouette of the skirt reminds me of those in Gone With the Wind, and is very much so iconic of the wealthy plantation ladies of the South during the Civil War. The fact that the flag is torn and tattered seems to me to be a reflection of the state of the country during that time,(very torn, get it?) and at the same time a bit of a commentary on the (usually) Southerners who put the American flag on anything and everything, but (sometimes, not always) degrade the fundamental American ideas of freedom and equality just as the south did and fought to continue doing during the civil war. Dixie Dâ€™Amelio: the little black dress with long white sleeves and big black hat definitely evoke old Hollywood legend Audrey Hepburn to me. Gabrielle Union: the fact that itâ€™s made of ocean plastic immediately brings to mind the fact that the US is the second largest plastic consumer in the world. Gigi Hadid: she seems to possibly be referencing Jessica Rabbit, and Who Framed Roger Rabbit is an American Film. (I know itâ€™s a bit weak, but I didnâ€™t say they were all super great references) Grimes: again, American Consumerism; this time with a nod to Silicon Valley. Also, the pen is mightier than the sword, maybe? Idk bout that one. Hunter Schafer: likely another reference to Silicon Valley. Lilâ€™ Nas X: That first look feels like heâ€™s representing the King of England in the American Revolution.

Â @thistagworkedÂ  I don't know which "60's" you're referencing, but America sure wasn't a "European melting pot" up until the 60's. I can agree that America has forced many cultures into assimilating into the WASP lifestyle. However, Indigenous people were here way before the Europeans ever crossed the Atlantic. Not to mention that black people were brought over during the slave trade in the 1600's and the Chinese were immigrating to the West Coast in the 1800's for the Gold Rush. Your reference of the 1960's may be referring to the Civil Rights Movement, but nonwhite cultures have always been in America and have shaped our country to be what it is today. Â @thistagworkedÂ  The Google definition of ethnicity is "the fact or state of belonging to a social group that has a common national or cultural tradition". You claim that diversity of ethnicities is fine, "but a nation can not stand without a common culture". So, how do you propose we reach a common culture when your idea of an American culture is limited to a "traditional Judeo-Christian centered nation". Given you think the diversity of ethnicities is fine, then why limit American culture to only select religions. Religion is a key element of ethnicity and the different ethnic cultures. I believe it is groups that follow a more "traditional Judeo-Christian" lifestyle, that are separating the nation (though I still believe in their right to practice said religion). I agree that politically we are divided beyond repair. To me, we should aim towards a diverse American culture. Together we can be united by the identity of being American, but still have pride in our individual ethnicities and heritage. Ultimately, you are only spreading hate by vilifying other religions and believing that different ethnicities can only live in harmony when they all assimilate to one blanket culture. America is a "salad bowl", not a melting pot. We should be able to distinguish between the different cultures and recognize everyone's unique experiences while still working in tandem with one another. You claimed that all white Americans are viewed the same because they had no problem assimilating to American culture. This is false. For example, Irish families sought refuge in America after the Potato Famine that I am sure you are aware of. Now, the Irish didn't simply assimilate to the Protestant American culture that was already established. Instead, they faced discrimination for having Catholic beliefs and were forced to find refuge in other places of America, trying to escape the negative responses from Protestants. Stores had signs stating "No Irish Need Apply"  making it hard for them to find work, often resorting to the lowest paying and most dangerous jobs available. As a result of these tensions, a Jesuit priest named John Bapst was tar and feathered by an anti-Catholic mob in the 1850's. I don't want to have to give you a whole history lesson but European immigrants received their own level of cultural discrimination and were FORCED to assimilate due to violence and intimidation. Your rhetoric makes it seem as though whites are more well mannered and just simply submitted for the sake of the country. Not to mention that black Americans today can barely track their history beyond great grand parents due to the slave trade. They were physically taken from their native land and the Colonial forces did not keep proper records for them to track their ancestry. Additionally, the genocide of Indigenous people quite literally wiped out their ancestors which is why they are so passionate about holding onto their culture in fear of it fading. So, in a way, I agree that it is a problem how most people are so unfamiliar with their ancestry and heritage. However, this is a result of the same ideology that you are pushing. To force people to assimilate is to wipe them of their history and push them into a belief or political system that they don't view as having a "solid moral standard", to use your own terminology. The "dreaded generic white American" that you reference is a result of hateful ideologies, not the supposed assimilated white culture. The idea of being "white Americans [that] despise themselves for being only an American" is ironic given white Americans currently hold the majority of societal power in America and tend to be the ones oppressing the other races. It more so seems that white people seek out their ancestry in hopes for that "1% African" statistic that can then justify their racist ideology. I feel as though you have some of the right ideas but are completely erasing the experiences of BIPOC individuals in this country who have had to overcome insane amounts of adversity but are still expected to change to make radical conservatives feel more comfortable.

RE: Lil Nas X  I fully disagree that he didn't follow the theme, and here's why.   Lil Nas X's journey through the music industry is also heavily intertwined with the relationship between Black men, conservative America, gayness, and Christianity (specifically, evangelical Christianity). By starting from a Pope-adjacent cloak that conceals 99% of himself, he is showing how American culture, which is heavily dictated by the Christian religion, forced him to conceal. Then, after being attacked, he had to protect himself from that cultural drag (the suit of armor), and his final bodysuit look showcases his own American independence... not only as a musical creator who can now release his artistry without death threats and damnation but also existing openly as a proud Black gay man.   His looks represent the new era of American independence: not from Britain, but from each other and from the grasp of cultural and religious figures that condemn anyone who doesn't agree with them or follow their doctrine. Queer liberation is absolutely 100% on-theme, and Lil Nas X did it PERFECTLY.

Okay, this is just a stupid idea coming from a girl who knows nothing about fashion, but the concept of Lil Nas X's three-part fashion event could actually have been pretty good and could have been right on theme. His three-part costume could have represented the story of America. The first part -- the imposing dress -- is actually perfect: it is the exact image of a monarch's dress, and it is golden and heavily embroidered, just like a crazy king with too much money and a big ego and no care at all for his subjects could have worn. Then Lil Nas X drops it, symbolically stripping America from its kingly clothes and stripping the king from his American colonies (hello hello, American Independence theme!) and then beneath it you can find clothes that embody a certain idea of America -- wealthy, heroic, proud America. The superhero type of look could have worked well, if it had had some heavy American symbolism, like colours or something. Then finally Lil Nas X drops that American look too, to reveal a third and final look -- one that could illustrate his beef with America and things that are wrong with America. Clothes in tatters for example to illustrate systemic poverty, signs of violence to show what the MAGA ideal is doing to gay people and black people -- I don't know, as I said I know nothing about fashion, but I think there was a way to showcase this sort of idea. Let's just say that initially when I saw the heavy golden robes I really thought Lil Nas X had gone with something like that -- apparently celebrating America and its independence only to show what its outdated and cruel ideals have done to this country.

Now I usually agree with you, however the Iman look definitely embodies American independence. America was built on the backs of slaves and the genocide of the Native peoples. So to Iman her take on American independence was a reference to her deep African roots and people who were enslaved and captured. I thought that her take on it was breathtaking and a beautiful tribute to enslaved people and how we were able to take back our freedom in America.

I watched (and loved) this video however, I did see an American Independence theme in some of the outfits that may not have broken all the way through. Kim Kardashian, for instance, might have been trying to say (with that blackout outfit) that there is no independence in America. At least for people of color. Lil Nas X might have been trying to say that he found his independence in America by shedding the various costumes assigned to him by our culture until he got down to the one that was appropriate to who he really is. Maybe I'm reading too much into these, but some of the outfits seemed to play on the absence of independence or freedom in modern day America. Especially outfits worn by people of color struck me as ironic in that way. Just my two cents.

I feel your 'acceptable' interpretations of the theme aren't being nearly flexible enough. People thought more outside the box and cleverly about their looks this year, and I think that's appropriate considering what happened in 2020 and is still very much happening. America is something to be critiqued, and I think a lot of the gowns did that in subtle, cheeky ways. Interpreting it just as "must be referencing an American designer or including a flag" is so limiting and not really the intention, at least not as I perceived it.   Take the look at 23:50. That is obviously another reference to Audrey Hepburn. I think it's actually super clever for a European designer to reference a European who made her fame in Hollywood, practically defined everything that came after, and eventually became an American fashion icon all without ever actually being American. Same goes for the one you named as being a ref to her at 39:14.   The "Peg the Patriarchy" look is TOTALLY on theme. Patriarchy is steeped into the very bones of the United States, and the top looks like a bulletproof vest or some kind of military gear. Having that statement on that piece and then having the tailored white pant just makes me think of going to war with the patriarchy and not caring who you have to F*ck to do it. that's a statement on America if I've ever heard one.   Grimes' sword was forged from a melted down gun and she looks like she's dressed for war- referencing the American inner conflict over the 2nd amendment. It's no coincidence her other hand is holding a book- the most vocal opponents of firearms are people who are highly educated and those who work in schools.   Lil Nas X went with looking at American excess- gold on gold on gold, lavish, taking something and making it so over-the-top that it's unbelievable. The final look was a very rock 'n roll style to me, just updated to be more sexy and less campy. I was a little shocked you called it out while literally having it facing, because it SCREAMS rock'n'roll to me. Elvis would have totally worn that... well, when he was more trim, anyway.   Olivia's look said Madonna meets punk rock to me, which suits both her musical trajectory and inspiration and fits the theme.   Some of the ones you praise highly were just so on-the-nose. Like, I feel like any third grader would come up with making a ballgown like the stripes on the flag. Having them be unwound and unfinished was a neat idea, but the overall concept was so boring. Anything that just said "Hey how can we use stars and stripes to make it American-y" missed an opportunity to do literally anything more interesting.

She mentioned how it was important to her to have the words of The New Colossus, the poem at the base of the Statue of Liberty,  incorporated to her look, and that is why she is wearing that purse. She even chose to have her makeup done this way to represent the American flag blowing in the wind. I agree the dress could have been much better, but when talking about sticking to theme, Amanda clearly put a lot of thought and effort into her look and I think she deserves credit for that!!

Â @poppyisyourmommy6956Â  you see it depends. I speak from Japanese studies experience, so it'll be different for other ethnicities. However, each time we held any event at which the students and some uni stuff would be dressed in kimono the Japanese people we encountered were over the moon to see us Europeans dressed in their traditional clothing. One thing was we knew how to do it, so it wasn't a bathing robe, some curtain around the waist and call it a day. They saw we cared, took the effort and appreciated part of their culture, that has been in decay for years now. Japanese people my age would know how to put on a yukata (summer cotton kimono, very casual) but with formal ones not at all. One girl from exchange was super impressed that I distinguished furisode (long sleeve maiden kimono) and knew the name, because even her classmates at home didn't know it.  So if you get dressed appropriately to show the respect to the culture, to educate those around you it's appreciation and would be welcomed. If you pretend you do and just do whatever for clout that's when it gets problematic and should be called out. What comes to my mind is many singers doing a "summer song MV" with a America's indigenous people's headdress, even though they've asked for years now to not do it. Ciaraâ€™s dress references her husbandâ€™s number and team. The NFL has this concept called the color rush uniform where teams will wear alternate colors and designs other than their standard home or away uniforms for one or two games a season. These uniforms are usually brightly colored and rely less on logos and design lines and more on color. Ciara is doing the Seahawks color rush uniform which is a bright, highlighter green from head to toe and is universally panned by football fans. The fact that sheâ€™s taken one of the most hated uniform designs in all of football and made it chic, topped off with her husbandâ€™s Super Bowl ring, makes both deep sports and fashion references and I love her for that.

My interpretation of her dress was to make people think, as fashion should.   On the front, it looks like a nice simple, off-the-shoulder tuxedo-inspired dress, a throwback to the white suit she wore when she was sworn in as a congresswoman. However, even the color white has a complicated history in the US. Commonly associated with the US women's suffragette movement of the 19th and 20th centuries, it was meant to symbolize purity, a term with a very complicated history in the US. One of the ways the US suffrage movement was successful was by playing into the stereotype that by them getting the ability to vote, they weren't challenging the status quo of men (especially white men) and the mainstream suffragette movement had several major figures who played up this dynamic and were racist and excluded BIPOC activists. Native Americans weren't granted full citizenship until 1924 with the Snyder Act and the 19th amendment was passed in 1920, meaning that any Native American couldn't technically vote until 1924 and they left enforcement up to states. As a result, some states either didn't care to extend voting resources to these communities or deliberately did so.   Fashion has always been political and anyone who says otherwise is naive. American politics has rapidly become polarized over years, and the American government's design benefits those who are partisan. Unlike many countries globally, the US doesn't have a parliamentary system in which minority governments can be formed. AOC has always stood firm in her beliefs, so I disagree with those criticizing her for not "reading the room." Now, I'll reveal my bias because I really like what she stands for as a politician. She had always made political choices regarding fashion; it's just another medium for her to express her beliefs. For instance, she wore red lipstick to her swearing-in because a consultant for Supreme Court Justice Sotomayor once told the future justice to wear nude nail polish to avoid any additional scrutiny. You cannot miss the racial, gender, ethnic connotations of that suggestion. Another instance could be found when she wore a red blazer to her speech condemning Rep. Yoho for calling her a "bitch". Society puts women or femme-presenting people down for enjoying stereotypical "girly things" and trying to be serious all the time. It's literally the plot of the iconic 2004 film "Legally Blonde" and they still do. God forbid, if a politician wants to partake in one of fashion's most important nights.   As for the message in the back, it's widely known that AOC heavily believes in increasing the taxes on the uber-wealthy. Fashion can be frivolous but at the end of the day, making clothes is a job and a multi-million dollar industry in the US that heavily depends on the exploitation of severely underpaid women both domestically and abroad. Fashion/clothes is also an art, so her showing up with a massive "Tax the Rich" message on the back to a fashion event where the biggest donors are often individuals who try to cheat the US tax system isn't a slap to any artisan or designer's face but a reminder that the fashion and art worlds have to innovate and move forward. You can have nice clothes and be environmentally friendly, the person making your clothes should have access to affordable/universal healthcare, artisans should be paid a living wage and the people who consume fashion and art should all pay into a more equitable tax system.   2020 was the first year in which Amazon paid a significant amount of taxes this year and in 2018, they paid no federal income tax and one doesn't have to be an accountant to tell you that Amazon did make any money that year, especially when we look at how much Jeff Bezos' wealth grew those two years. They got away with it because they knew how to game the US tax system. One of the ways that wealthy Americans get out of paying their tax bills is through philanthropy. I'm not saying all philanthropy is bad but people do definitely take advantage of it. Billionaires such as Michael Dell have said that he is more comfortable giving money to charity than giving it to the government, aka taxes. Yes, the government could better spend money in certain areas but there's something absurd about a nation who spends trillions of dollars on defense and wars every year but still can't scrape up enough money to purchase up-to-date textbooks for certain schools. While some wealthy individuals have generously spent their money on important causes such as public health or higher education, it is ridiculous for communities to depend on the generosity of rich people to fund public services especially in the US, an insanely wealthy country. Charity is nice but isn't and shouldn't be the government. Also, allowing the uber-wealthy to shirk out of paying their fair share only creates a more unequal country which isn't one that is very pleasant to live in. For example, it is important that everyone receives a nice, well-rounded K-12 education and not just those who happen to live in a district with a wealthy family who can fund an aviation-focused charter school (a real thing).   Long story short, AOC did "read the room" or wasn't being tacky. She has always made her fashion choices political and the Met Gala was going to be no exception. Fashion has always been political and it's important that the uber-wealthy pay more in taxes so we have a more equitable society (both her and my opinion). If anything, I wish the words on the back of her dress were embroidered instead of screen-printed and the dress was better fitted in the back.  *Edited for grammar

The fact that people KNEW that was Kim Kardashian (aside from questioning what the hell was going on)  says a lot about american culture and the impact or influence of this figures  (famous people) have in the country. On a side note it could also be referrencing the nowadays  occidental toxic standarts for beauty, that again have a lot to do with this A-list celebrities which somehow are connected with America since it's a country where a lot of them work, live, etc?.  To some people this may sound a bit arrogant from her part that Kim is basically  saying "hey, i am the moment and huge psrt of american culture" but there's a hint of truth at how much this people matters to america (talking of it as a nation) , how often they are idolized and put in a pedestal, and how somehow the high-class, holywood, elite celebrities had become a symbol, representation of  part of the United estates identity especial highlight since the patriotism of a country derives from national symbols, which is fundamental in any country. In relation with the last part, whether it's good or bad it's up to each person since we can't really discuss history or any social context/ocurrence from moralism. Finally I want to say that this is just my interpretation about the meaning behind the look, I don't claim to be any fashion critique or frar from it I am just giving my analysis about the costume and the relation with America.
